752
00:48:28.500 --> 00:48:30.090
<i>It gets dark by 5:00 p.m.</i>

753
00:48:32.880 --> 00:48:34.940
<i>If you wanna bullshit someone
about your vacancy rate.</i>

754
00:48:34.960 --> 00:48:37.790
you need lights shining
in all those unleased spaces by 4:30.

755
00:48:38.340 --> 00:48:40.710
I don't blame you for not doing it.
It's a lot of work.

756
00:48:40.790 --> 00:48:43.190
But those vacancies would
take you to 13.5 cents a square foot.

757
00:48:43.210 --> 00:48:44.300
We'll fill some of those.

758
00:48:44.380 --> 00:48:46.420
Let's call it 16 cents. Fair?

759
00:48:47.090 --> 00:48:52.420
That's a $1.383.000 valuation
at a 10% cap rate.

760
00:48:53.420 --> 00:48:56.170
But. of course a 10% cap rate
is too low for this market.

761
00:48:56.250 --> 00:48:58.920
My partners and I have multiple deals
with 12% returns.

762
00:48:59.670 --> 00:49:01.050
which would be...

763
00:49:01.130 --> 00:49:06.880
$1.152.533 underlying valuation.

764
00:49:08.630 --> 00:49:13.250
1.152.533.

765
00:49:15.170 --> 00:49:16.790
How do you do this in your head?

766
00:49:17.460 --> 00:49:19.540
There's no way I can do this math.

767
00:49:20.750 --> 00:49:23.170
Well. you know. maybe I could fake it?

768
00:49:23.920 --> 00:49:24.920
How?

769
00:49:27.090 --> 00:49:28.420
Practice.

770
00:49:28.500 --> 00:49:29.590
I'll just memorize it.

771
00:49:31.630 --> 00:49:32.670
All of it?

772
00:49:33.840 --> 00:49:35.300
Yeah. I got a pretty good memory.

773
00:49:36.250 --> 00:49:37.340
That good?

774
00:49:37.420 --> 00:49:39.130
Well. I got a week to learn it. right?

775
00:49:40.540 --> 00:49:42.000
Hustling a hustler.

776
00:49:42.090 --> 00:49:43.340
I love it.

777
00:49:44.540 --> 00:49:45.790
But. if this works.

778
00:49:46.460 --> 00:49:48.420
Renault's gonna challenge you
on the cap rate.

779
00:49:48.500 --> 00:49:50.540
So you need to get ready for it.

780
00:49:51.500 --> 00:49:53.790
Look. this is downtown.
The risk here is very low.

781
00:49:54.420 --> 00:49:56.000
It doesn't warrant a 12% return.

782
00:49:56.540 --> 00:49:58.250
I'm firm with a 10% cap rate.

783
00:49:58.750 --> 00:50:02.250
He's gonna try to hold you
to a 10% cap rate on the underlying value.

784
00:50:02.340 --> 00:50:03.840
which we're not gonna take.

785
00:50:04.340 --> 00:50:06.750
Not with a 25% premium going to him.

786
00:50:06.840 --> 00:50:09.210
But you're gonna need
somewhere to go in the conversation.

787
00:50:09.290 --> 00:50:12.750
So I want you to memorize
the 10.5% cap rate scenario as well.

788
00:50:12.840 --> 00:50:19.170
But a 25% premium on a 10.5% cap rate
is too high. right?

789
00:50:22.920 --> 00:50:28.050
10.5% cap rate means
$1.317.000 underlying.

790
00:50:28.130 --> 00:50:33.380
With the 25% premium. that's $1.646.250.

791
00:50:34.170 --> 00:50:35.250
Too high.

792
00:50:35.340 --> 00:50:37.420
Yeah. that sounds too high.

793
00:50:37.500 --> 00:50:40.290
You goddamn right it's too high.

794
00:50:42.590 --> 00:50:44.420
So maybe you can sell him a choice.

795
00:50:46.590 --> 00:50:47.960
Mr. Renault. I like you.

796
00:50:48.460 --> 00:50:51.210
First halfway decent golf game I've had
since I've moved here.

797
00:50:51.290 --> 00:50:55.130
But if you want us to value this building
at a 10% cap rate in a booming market.

798
00:50:55.210 --> 00:50:56.960
where we can get 12% elsewhere.

799
00:50:57.500 --> 00:51:00.500
we're not gonna give you
an instant 25% profit in the markup.

800
00:51:01.750 --> 00:51:02.750
Tell you what.

801
00:51:03.630 --> 00:51:04.880
I'll give you two options.

802
00:51:05.790 --> 00:51:11.090
We get an 11% capital return rate
and you get your 25% profit in the markup.

803
00:51:11.170 --> 00:51:17.420
or we get a 10.5% cap rate and you take
an 18% instead of a 25% markup.

804
00:51:17.880 --> 00:51:20.000
You can choose. But...

805
00:51:20.920 --> 00:51:22.210
he can't help you.

806
00:51:27.170 --> 00:51:29.130
You're not what I expected. Matt Steiner.

807
00:51:32.290 --> 00:51:33.380
I'll take the latter.

808
00:51:34.050 --> 00:51:35.050
Okay.

809
00:51:35.920 --> 00:51:36.960
How'd I do?

810
00:51:38.590 --> 00:51:40.250
You left 17.000 on the table.

811
00:51:41.840 --> 00:51:43.090
Oh. well.

812
00:51:43.170 --> 00:51:47.130
- What's the number?
- $1.554.060.

813
00:51:47.210 --> 00:51:52.170
But. we can call it an even 1.560.000
if you leave me that desk.

814
00:51:56.630 --> 00:51:57.960
I can't believe it worked.

815
00:51:58.630 --> 00:51:59.500
I can.

816
00:51:59.590 --> 00:52:01.340
Tomorrow we meet the tenants.

817
00:52:01.420 --> 00:52:04.340
introduce ourselves as Matt's partners.

818
00:52:04.420 --> 00:52:07.670
and watch the jaws drop.

819
00:52:11.670 --> 00:52:14.880
Maybe I should call a photographer
so you capture the moment.

820
00:52:14.960 --> 00:52:16.460
- Joe.
- What?

821
00:52:17.050 --> 00:52:18.340
Too much?

822
00:52:18.420 --> 00:52:20.290
Yeah. Cheers.

823
00:52:48.170 --> 00:52:49.630
Hello.

824
00:53:48.670 --> 00:53:49.670
Smile.

825
00:55:16.630 --> 00:55:18.290
Hi. Pop.

826
00:55:18.380 --> 00:55:20.500
How you doing?

827
00:55:20.590 --> 00:55:22.710
And who's this right here?
Who's this right here?

828
00:55:22.800 --> 00:55:23.840
Hey. Grandpa.

829
00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:28.000
Dad.

830
00:55:34.590 --> 00:55:36.730
- Here. get some of these sweet potatoes.
- No. thank you.

831
00:55:36.750 --> 00:55:39.090
What kind of growing boy
don't like sweet potato mash?

832
00:55:39.170 --> 00:55:41.130
Sweetie. try 'em. They're delicious.

833
00:55:41.210 --> 00:55:42.590
Daddy met the vice president.

834
00:55:43.250 --> 00:55:44.590
Really now?

835
00:55:44.670 --> 00:55:47.090
Yes. he did. Bernard is being modest.

836
00:55:48.460 --> 00:55:49.590
LBJ?

837
00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:52.540
Yes. sir. He came by the Bankers Building.

838
00:55:53.750 --> 00:55:54.840
Yes. son.

839
00:56:00.380 --> 00:56:01.920
Smooth. Very smooth.

840
00:56:02.590 --> 00:56:03.840
Thought you didn't smoke.

841
00:56:03.920 --> 00:56:04.920
No. I don't.

842
00:56:05.420 --> 00:56:06.920
But I know you like 'em. so...

843
00:56:07.420 --> 00:56:09.340
These are a lot nicer than what I smoke.

844
00:56:12.550 --> 00:56:15.130
You doing so well
out there in Los Angeles.

845
00:56:16.130 --> 00:56:17.250
Guess you were right.

846
00:56:17.920 --> 00:56:18.920
About what?

847
00:56:19.340 --> 00:56:21.290
Earning money the way white men do.

848
00:56:21.750 --> 00:56:23.670
Found you a place where you could do that.

849
00:56:24.670 --> 00:56:27.670
Still... no chance of doing that here.

850
00:56:28.170 --> 00:56:29.550
It might even be worse.

851
00:56:29.630 --> 00:56:32.630
No. it's not perfect in California. but...

852
00:56:33.920 --> 00:56:34.920
it is different.

853
00:56:35.840 --> 00:56:39.630
I don't... I don't think it's California.

854
00:56:42.500 --> 00:56:43.750
I'm proud of you. son.

855
00:56:59.090 --> 00:57:00.170
Where you going?

856
00:57:00.710 --> 00:57:02.000
Taking a walk through town.

857
00:57:04.750 --> 00:57:05.840
Dressed like that?

858
00:57:06.960 --> 00:57:09.000
Going on the other side of the tracks.

859
00:57:11.000 --> 00:57:12.500
You make sure you wear your tie.

860
00:57:13.750 --> 00:57:14.750
I planned on it.

861
00:57:18.380 --> 00:57:19.550
Take Junior with you.

862
00:57:21.880 --> 00:57:24.090
He needs to see where he comes from
up close.

863
00:58:14.460 --> 00:58:16.090
Why the fountains separated. Dad?

864
00:58:19.250 --> 00:58:20.880
It's just different down here. son.

865
00:58:21.840 --> 00:58:22.840
Yeah.

866
00:58:23.550 --> 00:58:24.920
I'm sorry you had to see that.

867
00:58:26.130 --> 00:58:27.130
It's okay.

868
00:58:28.040 --> 00:58:29.500
Hey. how much for a shine?

869
00:58:29.590 --> 00:58:31.090
Only do white folks here. sir.

870
00:58:45.130 --> 00:58:46.550
<i>You think this is a mistake?</i>

871
00:58:47.880 --> 00:58:49.590
I think the world is changing.

872
00:58:51.460 --> 00:58:53.840
But maybe it hasn't changed enough
in Texas.

873
00:58:57.380 --> 00:58:58.880
I feel like I have to do this.

874
00:59:01.420 --> 00:59:02.550
I know.

875
00:59:03.550 --> 00:59:05.290
And that is why I support you.

876
00:59:08.040 --> 00:59:09.840
What the hell do we know about banking?

877
00:59:10.340 --> 00:59:13.880
Banks take deposits and make loans.
mostly on property.

878
00:59:14.550 --> 00:59:18.000
Owning a bank is like owning the other
side of the real estate business.

879
00:59:18.090 --> 00:59:21.290
I'm pretty sure there's a few complexities
you just left out.

880
00:59:21.920 --> 00:59:26.500
Like we black.
and this goddamn bank is in Texas.

881
00:59:26.590 --> 00:59:29.460
There's no Texas law
that says we can't own a bank.

882
00:59:29.550 --> 00:59:33.130
I concede. us being black
may be an issue. practically speaking.

883
00:59:33.210 --> 00:59:35.000
You willing to concede that?

884
00:59:35.090 --> 00:59:36.710
Well. we get Matt to front for us.

885
00:59:36.790 --> 00:59:37.880
No shit.

886
00:59:37.960 --> 00:59:40.460
But here in LA
Matt unlocks the doors for us.

887
00:59:40.550 --> 00:59:42.210
he don't run the business day-to-day.

888
00:59:42.290 --> 00:59:45.250
much less a banking business.
which is not simple.

889
00:59:45.340 --> 00:59:46.920
We'd have to monitor things closely.

890
00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:48.710
And how the hell you plan to do that?

891
00:59:48.790 --> 00:59:51.460
We can't set foot in a bank in Texas
unless we're the help.

892
00:59:51.920 --> 00:59:53.750
I thought that would be
your favorite part.

893
00:59:53.840 --> 00:59:55.090
I live in LA.

894
00:59:55.170 --> 00:59:57.590
I don't plan on moving to Texas. Do you?

895
00:59:57.670 --> 00:59:59.000
During the business week.

896
00:59:59.090 --> 01:00:01.960
And work as a janitor in a bank you own?

897
01:00:02.040 --> 01:00:03.040
Won't have to.

898
01:00:03.130 --> 01:00:06.000
Matt comes to me with the bank business
at the end of every day.

899
01:00:06.090 --> 01:00:09.170
What makes you think he's willing to move
to the middle of nowhere?

900
01:00:09.250 --> 01:00:12.040
No offense to your cosmopolitan hometown.

901
01:00:12.500 --> 01:00:16.170
Plus Matt's got a pretty good gig here.

902
01:00:16.250 --> 01:00:17.790
We'd have to make it worth his while.

903
01:00:17.880 --> 01:00:21.710
Great. so now we gonna pay him even more
money than we pay him to be white.

904
01:00:22.670 --> 01:00:26.250
Joe. think about all the good we can do
for the Negro community down there.

905
01:00:26.670 --> 01:00:28.500
Help 'em buy homes. start businesses.

906
01:00:29.670 --> 01:00:32.960
And aside from all that.
that bank is undervalued.

907
01:00:34.300 --> 01:00:37.250
There's enough capital
to double its loan base.

908
01:00:37.710 --> 01:00:39.000
We could make a lot of money.

909
01:00:39.090 --> 01:00:40.790
We make a lot of money now.

910
01:00:41.550 --> 01:00:43.420
You gonna stand there with a straight face

911
01:00:43.500 --> 01:00:46.500
and tell me there's a business argument
to do this?

912
01:00:46.590 --> 01:00:48.750
This is social activism. Bernard.

913
01:00:48.840 --> 01:00:49.840
Plain and simple.

914
01:00:50.250 --> 01:00:52.130
There's plenty other ways to do that.

915
01:00:53.040 --> 01:00:56.170
Or maybe you're feeling guilty about
leaving your father behind.

916
01:00:56.250 --> 01:00:57.250
Let me tell you this.

917
01:00:57.790 --> 01:01:01.840
If one trip home can
cripple your rational functions like this.

918
01:01:01.920 --> 01:01:02.920
we in trouble.

919
01:01:04.460 --> 01:01:05.710
With all due respect. Joe.

920
01:01:05.790 --> 01:01:07.840
I think this is something
you won't understand.

921
01:01:07.920 --> 01:01:08.920
I'm sorry.

922
01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:10.710
Did I not wake up black this morning?

923
01:01:10.790 --> 01:01:12.290
'Cause I'm pretty sure I did.

924
01:01:12.790 --> 01:01:14.340
Yep. still black.

925
01:01:14.420 --> 01:01:18.670
Are you telling me because I grew up
in California with a little bit of money.

926
01:01:18.750 --> 01:01:20.460
I'm not black in your eyes?

927
01:01:20.840 --> 01:01:22.540
I wasn't trying to make this personal.

928
01:01:24.420 --> 01:01:25.460
Yes. you were.

929
01:01:29.670 --> 01:01:30.710
I'm sorry.

930
01:01:34.130 --> 01:01:36.500
Bernard. if we go down to Texas

931
01:01:36.590 --> 01:01:39.170
and start screwing around with Jim Crow.
we gonna lose.

932
01:01:39.250 --> 01:01:40.960
Don't matter whether it's legal or not.

933
01:01:41.460 --> 01:01:44.250
Even if Dr. King
gets civil rights legislation.

934
01:01:44.340 --> 01:01:45.800
it ain't gonna happen fast enough

935
01:01:45.880 --> 01:01:48.340
for us to get out of this
without losing our shirts.

936
01:01:51.300 --> 01:01:52.630
Bring your father out here.

937
01:01:52.710 --> 01:01:54.040
Help him directly.

938
01:01:54.380 --> 01:01:57.460
And get rid of that notion that you can
save every black man in Texas.

939
01:01:57.540 --> 01:01:58.790
'cause you can't.

940
01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:02.420
I understand if you don't want to
partner with me on it.

941
01:02:03.500 --> 01:02:05.630
You can't buy this bank
on your own. Bernard.

942
01:02:05.710 --> 01:02:06.710
Not at that price.

943
01:02:07.130 --> 01:02:09.130
Then I'll find someone else
to do it with me.

944
01:02:12.130 --> 01:02:13.670
Jesus H. Christ.

945
01:02:15.710 --> 01:02:18.170
I told you getting rich
was going to change you.

946
01:02:21.130 --> 01:02:25.250
Mark my words. This is a bad idea.

947
01:02:26.130 --> 01:02:29.920
But it's even more bodacious
than us buying that Bankers Building.

948
01:02:30.380 --> 01:02:32.380
And we sure enough pulled that off.
didn't we?

949
01:02:35.920 --> 01:02:37.500
All right. I'm in.

950
01:02:39.460 --> 01:02:40.500
Shit.

951
01:02:49.540 --> 01:02:53.590
For the record I say you guys are out of
your minds. completely out of your minds.

952
01:02:53.670 --> 01:02:54.670
You ready?

953
01:02:55.210 --> 01:02:56.250
I...

954
01:02:56.340 --> 01:02:58.670
Could you tell me how a bank works
in three sentences?

955
01:03:00.920 --> 01:03:04.090
A bakery makes a profit by selling bread
for more than it cost to make.

956
01:03:04.710 --> 01:03:05.710
A bank makes a profit

957
01:03:05.790 --> 01:03:09.630
by selling loans for more than it costs to
get the money needed to make those loans.

958
01:03:09.710 --> 01:03:12.710
Basically. a bank gets money
from depositors at 3%

959
01:03:12.790 --> 01:03:13.920
and loans it out at five.

960
01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:16.670
Wow. That actually was three sentences.

961
01:03:18.920 --> 01:03:19.920
Let's go.

962
01:03:21.090 --> 01:03:22.130
This should be fun.

963
01:03:23.040 --> 01:03:24.170
You gonna put the hat on?

964
01:03:24.250 --> 01:03:25.250
I'll pass.

965
01:03:25.710 --> 01:03:26.710
All righty then.

966
01:03:27.300 --> 01:03:28.420
Shall we?

967
01:03:37.710 --> 01:03:40.210
Gentlemen. Don Silverthorne.

968
01:03:41.250 --> 01:03:42.440
- Robert Florance.
- Matt Steiner.

969
01:03:42.460 --> 01:03:43.460
Robert Florance Jr.

970
01:03:44.710 --> 01:03:46.460
- Next.
- Please. gentlemen. come in.

971
01:03:46.540 --> 01:03:47.630
Thank you.

972
01:03:49.420 --> 01:03:51.210
Yes. of course. Gentlemen.

973
01:03:54.710 --> 01:03:58.500
My son's guaranteed a position
to protect my remaining 20% interest?

974
01:03:58.590 --> 01:03:59.730
You'll see that in the addendum.

975
01:03:59.750 --> 01:04:02.380
But he won't be the bank's
exclusive loan officer any longer.

976
01:04:02.460 --> 01:04:05.840
My clients' primary interest in buying
the bank is to increase the loan volume

977
01:04:05.920 --> 01:04:07.710
and thus the profitability of the bank.

978
01:04:07.790 --> 01:04:11.170
He'll be reporting directly to you
as the new bank president. Mr. Steiner?

979
01:04:11.250 --> 01:04:12.250
That's right.

980
01:04:14.250 --> 01:04:17.210
Who are Bernard Garrett and Joseph Morris?

981
01:04:18.210 --> 01:04:19.840
My financial partners in Los Angeles.

982
01:04:38.960 --> 01:04:40.090
Why aren't they here?

983
01:04:40.460 --> 01:04:43.380
Honestly? Because they're
too rich to bother.

984
01:04:43.460 --> 01:04:44.880
That's why they have me.

985
01:04:44.960 --> 01:04:47.650
No offense. but they have hundreds
of these investments across the country.

986
01:04:47.670 --> 01:04:49.050
Well. that's great for them.

987
01:04:49.710 --> 01:04:51.920
But this is the investment
they're closing today.

988
01:05:10.630 --> 01:05:13.380
I should note that
the full purchase price for the bank

989
01:05:13.460 --> 01:05:16.630
is sitting in escrow in my bank
as of 11:00 a.m. this morning.

990
01:05:16.710 --> 01:05:18.590
Which is all that matters.

991
01:05:29.170 --> 01:05:33.590
Congratulations. you are now
the owner of your hometown bank.

992
01:05:34.790 --> 01:05:36.920
Time to get my black ass back to LA.

993
01:05:39.380 --> 01:05:40.460
Don't ask.

994
01:05:45.210 --> 01:05:47.920
My partners and I now own Mainland Bank.

995
01:05:48.500 --> 01:05:53.040
And we intend to change the bank's
policies regarding loans to Negroes.

996
01:05:54.170 --> 01:05:56.090
<i>But we need your help to identify</i>

997
01:05:56.170 --> 01:05:59.300
<i>responsible potential borrowers
in your congregations.</i>

998
01:05:59.920 --> 01:06:02.420
You get the loan...

999
01:06:02.500 --> 01:06:05.960
<i>Now. it goes without saying that we cannot
draw attention to this new policy</i>

1000
01:06:06.050 --> 01:06:08.540
<i>or to our ownership of the bank.</i>

1001
01:06:10.050 --> 01:06:13.590
<i>Or everything we're trying to do
will be put in jeopardy.</i>

1002
01:06:15.130 --> 01:06:19.550
<i>But make no mistake.
our goal is to foster business growth</i>

1003
01:06:19.630 --> 01:06:24.170
<i>and home ownership in our community
through access to capital.</i>

1004
01:06:24.920 --> 01:06:27.920
Thanks to your loan.
we bought two new pieces of equipment.

1005
01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:29.880
Doubled our revenue in three months.

1006
01:06:37.880 --> 01:06:40.750
You approved 14 new loans this week?

1007
01:06:41.670 --> 01:06:42.920
That sounds right.

1008
01:06:43.340 --> 01:06:44.840
Only five of those were mine.

1009
01:06:46.630 --> 01:06:48.960
There's a lot of underutilized capital
in this bank.

1010
01:06:49.460 --> 01:06:52.440
You knew I was gonna start signing off
on loans directly to jump-start things.

1011
01:06:52.460 --> 01:06:54.440
I haven't seen
that many viable applicants in one week

1012
01:06:54.460 --> 01:06:55.840
since I've worked at this bank.

1013
01:06:56.380 --> 01:06:58.540
I've been working here
since I was 18 years old.

1014
01:06:59.250 --> 01:07:00.960
Where are you finding all these people?

1015
01:07:01.750 --> 01:07:04.340
Who's "Solomon Johnson"?

1016
01:07:06.170 --> 01:07:07.460
We're casting a wide net.

1017
01:07:08.050 --> 01:07:10.170
The more loans we make.
the higher our profit.

1018
01:07:10.790 --> 01:07:11.960
Goes for your stake too.

1019
01:07:12.500 --> 01:07:13.840
As long as they don't default.

1020
01:07:15.250 --> 01:07:16.540
That's what collateral's for.

1021
01:07:52.880 --> 01:07:56.050
My partner Joe comes in town
every other week from LA.

1022
01:07:56.540 --> 01:07:57.730
He's looking forward to meeting you.

1023
01:07:57.750 --> 01:07:59.880
I told him this is
the best barbecue around here.

1024
01:07:59.960 --> 01:08:00.790
Thank you.

1025
01:08:00.880 --> 01:08:03.540
Look. the books I keep are pretty simple.

1026
01:08:04.090 --> 01:08:06.500
But I can go back to the office
and bring 'em out.

1027
01:08:06.590 --> 01:08:07.590
You can look 'em over.

1028
01:08:07.670 --> 01:08:09.380
- That would be great. Thank you.
- Okay.

1029
01:08:13.790 --> 01:08:14.880
You're late.

1030
01:08:15.960 --> 01:08:17.540
Florance discovered the black loans.

1031
01:08:18.790 --> 01:08:22.050
He's been wary of me from the beginning.
now he's watching me like a hawk.

1032
01:08:22.540 --> 01:08:23.540
Any reason why?

1033
01:08:23.630 --> 01:08:25.500
Well. yeah. he had dreams
of being the boss.

1034
01:08:25.590 --> 01:08:28.540
not reporting to some guy from California
ten years younger than him.

1035
01:09:08.380 --> 01:09:09.380
I hate it here.

1036
01:09:12.590 --> 01:09:15.210
Come on.
We've only been here three months.

1037
01:09:15.290 --> 01:09:16.420
It's enough time to know.

1038
01:09:19.090 --> 01:09:20.750
Why did you agree to do this?

1039
01:09:21.420 --> 01:09:23.210
I'm making 25.000 a year.

1040
01:09:23.290 --> 01:09:25.750
We bought this house
with one month's salary.

1041
01:09:25.840 --> 01:09:28.600
When you started with them you said
they were gonna make you a partner.

1042
01:09:28.630 --> 01:09:30.800
- Yeah. and...
- A partner isn't on a salary.

1043
01:09:30.880 --> 01:09:32.000
A partner is an owner.

1044
01:09:32.840 --> 01:09:35.090
Isn't that what you always told me
you wanted to be?

1045
01:09:35.170 --> 01:09:36.880
And I will be.

1046
01:09:38.380 --> 01:09:39.880
You know. on the next bank we buy.

1047
01:09:42.710 --> 01:09:44.000
You're buying another one?

1048
01:09:46.210 --> 01:09:47.590
We're thinking about it. yeah.

1049
01:09:51.670 --> 01:09:53.250
Now that would be something.

1050
01:09:54.460 --> 01:09:55.460
Wouldn't it?

1051
01:10:00.210 --> 01:10:02.840
So. we all agree
the barbecue place is a good bet. right?

1052
01:10:11.500 --> 01:10:13.340
You must be Bernard Garrett.

1053
01:10:15.040 --> 01:10:16.340
And you're Joe Morris?

1054
01:10:16.420 --> 01:10:17.540
What. you follow me here?

1055
01:10:17.630 --> 01:10:19.840
Just trying to understand
who really owns my bank.

1056
01:10:28.040 --> 01:10:29.420
You boys are famous.

1057
01:10:32.040 --> 01:10:34.840
That's you and Vice President Johnson.
if I'm not mistaken.

1058
01:10:39.590 --> 01:10:40.590
Listen.

1059
01:10:42.170 --> 01:10:44.170
I've got nothing against
you people personally.

1060
01:10:44.250 --> 01:10:45.920
That's mighty white of you.

1061
01:10:46.000 --> 01:10:48.040
But if this town found out

1062
01:10:48.130 --> 01:10:52.090
that not only was their bank
regularly making loans to Negroes.

1063
01:10:53.090 --> 01:10:54.750
but was actually owned by two of 'em.

1064
01:10:56.210 --> 01:10:57.540
there'd be a run on the bank.

1065
01:10:58.630 --> 01:11:00.090
Well. why would they find out?

1066
01:11:02.130 --> 01:11:03.750
They don't have access to our books.

1067
01:11:04.130 --> 01:11:04.960
You do.

1068
01:11:05.040 --> 01:11:06.840
Took you three months to figure it out.

1069
01:11:07.920 --> 01:11:09.800
- I could tell 'em.
- Yeah. you could.

1070
01:11:09.880 --> 01:11:12.750
Then you'd own 20% of a failed bank
instead of a booming one.

1071
01:11:15.000 --> 01:11:16.040
What do you want?

1072
01:11:17.710 --> 01:11:18.960
To protect my investment.

1073
01:11:19.800 --> 01:11:23.670
This bank collapses. my 20% is worthless.

1074
01:11:24.960 --> 01:11:26.590
So. we're in this together?

1075
01:11:27.290 --> 01:11:28.500
Not quite.

1076
01:11:28.590 --> 01:11:31.250
See. my father didn't know
he was selling his bank to two Negroes.

1077
01:11:31.340 --> 01:11:33.800
so that's fraud.

1078
01:11:34.290 --> 01:11:35.880
I don't know about that. Bob.

1079
01:11:36.500 --> 01:11:40.210
See. both our names
were on that bank contract you signed.

1080
01:11:40.290 --> 01:11:42.130
You even asked about us.

1081
01:11:42.840 --> 01:11:44.170
Don't know who told you that.

1082
01:11:44.250 --> 01:11:46.670
Didn't have to be told. I was there.

1083
01:11:47.210 --> 01:11:48.540
No. you weren't.

1084
01:11:50.590 --> 01:11:51.630
Bring back memories?

1085
01:11:54.420 --> 01:11:56.840
And for the record. your father knew.

1086
01:11:58.670 --> 01:11:59.670
You're lying.

1087
01:11:59.750 --> 01:12:03.540
Ask him. or I can find a letter
where he and Silverthorne discussed it.

1088
01:12:06.380 --> 01:12:08.000
You boys think you're so smart.

1089
01:12:08.090 --> 01:12:09.130
We are.

1090
01:12:09.670 --> 01:12:11.050
For a couple colored boys.

1091
01:12:13.130 --> 01:12:14.690
You couldn't just make a loan
here. there to your kind.

1092
01:12:14.710 --> 01:12:16.960
You had to make 19 of them
right off the bat?

1093
01:12:19.800 --> 01:12:21.250
Well. here's another letter.

1094
01:12:21.340 --> 01:12:24.750
This one's from the Comptroller of
the Currency. The US Treasury Department.

1095
01:12:24.840 --> 01:12:27.920
They're moving our yearly inspection up
two quarters.

1096
01:12:28.000 --> 01:12:29.340
That's a month from now.

1097
01:12:29.420 --> 01:12:32.210
Because of anonymous reports
we're making unsafe loans.

1098
01:12:33.710 --> 01:12:37.170
You think you have this town figured out.
when you moved here three months ago?

1099
01:12:38.380 --> 01:12:39.460
Well. you don't.

1100
01:12:39.880 --> 01:12:40.880
I was born here.

1101
01:12:40.960 --> 01:12:44.000
So was I. In this house.

1102
01:12:47.800 --> 01:12:48.920
Well.

1103
01:12:49.460 --> 01:12:52.340
then you should've known
you couldn't keep this a secret very long.

1104
01:13:14.500 --> 01:13:18.000
We're gonna have to stop giving out loans
to Negroes until after this inspection.

1105
01:13:18.090 --> 01:13:20.500
What about the ones already on the books?

1106
01:13:22.670 --> 01:13:24.170
Can I propose something?

1107
01:13:24.250 --> 01:13:25.790
Can I get a stiff drink?

1108
01:13:27.920 --> 01:13:29.420
We should buy another bank.

1109
01:13:29.500 --> 01:13:30.920
Make that a double.

1110
01:13:31.960 --> 01:13:33.290
What? No. I'm...

1111
01:13:33.380 --> 01:13:34.500
I'm serious.

1112
01:13:43.460 --> 01:13:45.250
Okay. the Bank of Marlin is small.

1113
01:13:45.340 --> 01:13:48.000
You can purchase it outright for 274.000.

1114
01:13:48.090 --> 01:13:50.630
half of what you paid for 80% of Mainland.

1115
01:13:50.710 --> 01:13:51.960
As president of both banks.

1116
01:13:52.040 --> 01:13:55.250
I could move all the Negro loans
we made at Mainland to the Bank of Marlin

1117
01:13:55.340 --> 01:13:56.960
before Mainland gets inspected.

1118
01:13:57.420 --> 01:13:59.670
It should keep the government
out of our business

1119
01:13:59.750 --> 01:14:01.750
and hopefully make Florance an ally.

1120
01:14:02.210 --> 01:14:03.420
It's an interesting idea.

1121
01:14:03.500 --> 01:14:07.710
but Joe and I don't have
$274.000 in cash laying around.

1122
01:14:08.420 --> 01:14:11.800
And I doubt Silverthorne will finance us
buying another bank in Texas.

1123
01:14:11.880 --> 01:14:14.590
Right. well. I think I have
a solution to that.

1124
01:14:15.630 --> 01:14:17.630
The Bank of Marlin has
two million in deposits.

1125
01:14:17.710 --> 01:14:19.460
but it's only made one million in loans.

1126
01:14:19.550 --> 01:14:21.210
Which is why it's not making a profit.

1127
01:14:21.290 --> 01:14:22.340
So. we buy the bank.

1128
01:14:22.420 --> 01:14:25.670
We use that extra million in deposits
to purchase loans from an aggregator.

1129
01:14:26.040 --> 01:14:30.920
I've already identified a package of loans
with an 8% interest offered at 6.5%.

1130
01:14:31.000 --> 01:14:34.210
That 1.5% spread
puts the bank instantly in profit.

1131
01:14:34.290 --> 01:14:35.880
Unless there's a high default rate.

1132
01:14:35.960 --> 01:14:37.540
Check the underlying loans yourself.

1133
01:14:37.630 --> 01:14:39.210
They seem rock-solid to me.

1134
01:14:39.290 --> 01:14:41.880
The whole package is for sale
for 971.000.

1135
01:14:41.960 --> 01:14:45.090
Yeah. that doesn't help
the cash flow problem for Joe and me.

1136
01:14:45.170 --> 01:14:49.040
All right. it doesn't.
but if you and Joe incorporate as brokers.

1137
01:14:49.130 --> 01:14:51.000
the Bank of Marlin
can pay you a commission

1138
01:14:51.090 --> 01:14:53.710
of close to 200.000
on that package of mortgages.

1139
01:14:53.790 --> 01:14:57.540
That's an awful lot of commission
on a million-dollar package of mortgages.

1140
01:14:57.630 --> 01:14:59.710
Maybe. but it's completely legal.

1141
01:14:59.790 --> 01:15:01.380
It cuts your investment by two-thirds.

1142
01:15:01.460 --> 01:15:04.380
The bank stays profitable
and we keep loaning to Negroes.

1143
01:15:04.460 --> 01:15:05.460
Everyone wins.

1144
01:15:05.550 --> 01:15:07.000
It sounds too good to be true.

1145
01:15:07.460 --> 01:15:09.210
Well. then have your lawyers check.

1146
01:15:10.290 --> 01:15:13.040
Look. Matt. even if it does check out.

1147
01:15:13.840 --> 01:15:17.210
Joe has to spend his time in LA
overseeing our properties there.

1148
01:15:17.710 --> 01:15:20.130
And I'm here
overseeing you and Mainland Bank.

1149
01:15:20.210 --> 01:15:22.500
which I can't even get in
the front door of.

1150
01:15:23.880 --> 01:15:27.590
I just don't think it's the right time
for us to pick up a second bank in Texas.

1151
01:15:27.670 --> 01:15:30.170
Well. you won't have to.
if you let me run this one.

1152
01:15:31.000 --> 01:15:32.000
I mean really run it.

1153
01:15:34.790 --> 01:15:35.790
Matt.

1154
01:15:36.880 --> 01:15:39.630
I can't speak for Joe.
but I'm not comfortable with that.

1155
01:15:40.710 --> 01:15:43.000
I'm sorry to interrupt.

1156
01:15:43.090 --> 01:15:44.170
Would you like one?

1157
01:15:44.250 --> 01:15:45.340
- No.
- Okay.

1158
01:15:55.420 --> 01:15:58.130
Look. we agreed I'd co-own the next bank.

1159
01:15:58.210 --> 01:15:59.590
We even put it in the contract.

1160
01:16:00.000 --> 01:16:02.480
Three months ago. you didn't know
the first thing about banking.

1161
01:16:02.500 --> 01:16:04.020
Come on. I've learnt a lot in that time.

1162
01:16:04.040 --> 01:16:06.340
It's not that I don't have faith in you.
it's just...

1163
01:16:07.380 --> 01:16:08.380
What?

1164
01:16:09.340 --> 01:16:13.800
It's $274.000 of Joe's and my money.

1165
01:16:14.550 --> 01:16:16.800
We should at least
have the final say. right?

1166
01:16:21.090 --> 01:16:22.460
If I can't become my own man here.

1167
01:16:22.550 --> 01:16:24.670
then I think I need to resign
and go back to LA.

1168
01:16:27.340 --> 01:16:29.880
- Is this you blackmailing us?
- No.

1169
01:16:30.590 --> 01:16:31.710
No. that's not fair. Joe.

1170
01:16:31.790 --> 01:16:33.290
You guys have taught me so much.

1171
01:16:33.380 --> 01:16:34.800
I just wanna be more like you.

1172
01:16:35.210 --> 01:16:36.210
An owner.

1173
01:16:37.500 --> 01:16:38.920
Whatever you decide...

1174
01:16:40.340 --> 01:16:42.920
I really appreciate
everything you guys have done for me.

1175
01:16:46.920 --> 01:16:49.170
You said this was gonna be complicated.

1176
01:16:49.250 --> 01:16:53.340
What I said was. "This is a bad idea."

1177
01:16:54.630 --> 01:16:58.130
Then I agreed to drive off the cliff
with you and here we are.

1178
01:16:59.090 --> 01:17:03.920
Now. we gotta buy a kid with 90 days of
banking experience his own goddamn bank.

1179
01:17:05.710 --> 01:17:06.790
Without a chaperone.

1180
01:17:14.840 --> 01:17:18.630
Hey. everyone. I just wanted to say
I'm excited to work with all of you.

1181
01:17:18.710 --> 01:17:20.750
We're gonna do great things
with this bank.

1182
01:17:20.840 --> 01:17:24.380
Growing it while helping the community
around it grow at the same time.

1183
01:17:25.790 --> 01:17:26.960
My door is always open.

1184
01:17:27.710 --> 01:17:29.500
Let's show the public our new face.

1185
01:17:41.420 --> 01:17:44.090
Twelfth loan in the package.
it's that one right there.

1186
01:17:45.090 --> 01:17:47.340
Another beautiful house
in a white neighborhood.

1187
01:17:47.420 --> 01:17:48.590
Give it a five.

1188
01:17:51.500 --> 01:17:52.710
Thank you for doing this.

1189
01:17:54.670 --> 01:17:56.130
How else am I supposed to learn?

1190
01:18:06.300 --> 01:18:07.300
You can stop.

1191
01:18:07.380 --> 01:18:09.590
There's no one here
to see you cleaning anymore.

1192
01:18:09.670 --> 01:18:12.090
Whatever I do. I try to do my best.

1193
01:18:16.000 --> 01:18:17.460
I'm sorry you have to wear that.

1194
01:18:18.790 --> 01:18:21.380
I wish they'd just trust me.
then you wouldn't have to.

1195
01:18:22.210 --> 01:18:23.750
Do you resent me being here?

1196
01:18:26.540 --> 01:18:27.540
A little.

1197
01:18:31.130 --> 01:18:33.340
Do you resent me
for wanting to run my own bank?

1198
01:18:36.170 --> 01:18:37.170
A little.

1199
01:18:38.090 --> 01:18:39.130
Really?

1200
01:18:41.380 --> 01:18:43.420
Come on. You know
I wasn't born into money.

1201
01:18:44.090 --> 01:18:46.000
I just learnt to fake it.
And you helped me.

1202
01:18:49.340 --> 01:18:50.380
I do realize...

1203
01:18:51.340 --> 01:18:52.960
I had to be white for that to work.

1204
01:18:54.420 --> 01:18:55.460
And a man.

1205
01:18:58.500 --> 01:18:59.500
I just...

1206
01:19:01.210 --> 01:19:03.840
I wanna be respected
for what I've done for the business.

1207
01:19:06.170 --> 01:19:07.880
Respect is a big thing.

1208
01:19:08.540 --> 01:19:11.630
Sometimes people take big risks
to chase it.

1209
01:19:12.880 --> 01:19:15.130
I want this bank to succeed
just as much as you do.

1210
01:19:15.210 --> 01:19:16.590
I want you to succeed.

1211
01:19:17.590 --> 01:19:19.790
And I hope you don't take this
the wrong way.

1212
01:19:20.790 --> 01:19:23.460
but you just took up banking
three months ago.

1213
01:19:26.210 --> 01:19:27.210
So did Bernard.

1214
01:19:37.920 --> 01:19:38.920
They're all solid.

1215
01:19:39.000 --> 01:19:41.420
We looked at the property
securing every single loan.

1216
01:19:41.920 --> 01:19:43.040
That was fast.

1217
01:19:43.130 --> 01:19:47.000
Just be sure the documentation matches
exactly before handing over any money.

1218
01:19:47.090 --> 01:19:47.920
Yeah. of course.

1219
01:19:48.000 --> 01:19:50.250
And contact that lawyer I told you about
in Houston.

1220
01:19:50.340 --> 01:19:53.250
I worked with him before.
O'Keefe. Michael O'Keefe. I trust him.

1221
01:19:53.340 --> 01:19:54.850
I already did. He said he'll be there.

1222
01:19:54.880 --> 01:19:55.880
Perfect.

1223
01:19:56.420 --> 01:19:57.420
Excuse me.

1224
01:19:58.300 --> 01:19:59.710
Man. this place is so good.

1225
01:20:00.790 --> 01:20:02.790
So. I'm gonna head back in the morning.

1226
01:20:04.790 --> 01:20:06.170
It's okay.

1227
01:20:07.000 --> 01:20:08.840
I'll have it fixed in no time.

1228
01:20:16.300 --> 01:20:17.460
Okay.

1229
01:20:25.420 --> 01:20:27.750
<i>I thought his statement
was rather cautiously worded.</i>

1230
01:20:27.840 --> 01:20:30.710
<i>I didn't get any assurances
that Mr. Khrushchev or the Soviet Union</i>

1231
01:20:30.790 --> 01:20:32.960
<i>was out of the space race at all.</i>

1232
01:20:33.040 --> 01:20:33.880
<i>I think it's...</i>

1233
01:20:33.960 --> 01:20:37.590
Mr. Steiner. your attorney's almost
finished reviewing the packet of loans.

1234
01:20:37.670 --> 01:20:38.710
Great.

1235
01:20:45.340 --> 01:20:47.170
- Let me know if you need anything.
- Thanks.

1236
01:20:47.710 --> 01:20:50.290
Thank you again for doing this so quickly.

1237
01:20:50.710 --> 01:20:52.340
How are the underlying loans looking?

1238
01:20:52.420 --> 01:20:54.880
Solid. You can start
signing the contracts now.

1239
01:20:54.960 --> 01:20:55.960
Great.

1240
01:21:19.050 --> 01:21:20.210
- Hi.
- Hey.

1241
01:21:23.210 --> 01:21:24.460
Hi. How are you?

1242
01:21:24.540 --> 01:21:25.590
Good. how are you?

1243
01:21:25.670 --> 01:21:26.920
Good.

1244
01:21:27.000 --> 01:21:28.050
How'd it go?

1245
01:21:29.130 --> 01:21:32.090
Well. I just wrote a check for $971.000.

1246
01:21:32.790 --> 01:21:33.790
Never done that before.

1247
01:21:34.340 --> 01:21:35.880
You're a natural businessman.

1248
01:21:36.750 --> 01:21:38.170
I don't know. I mean...

1249
01:21:38.710 --> 01:21:41.350
tell that to the people who invested
in the drive-in ice cream shop.

1250
01:21:41.380 --> 01:21:42.500
You were 19.

1251
01:21:42.920 --> 01:21:45.340
Yeah. But. I dunno.
it was my dad's savings.

1252
01:21:45.420 --> 01:21:48.130
I just don't want to lose
Bernard and Joe's money the same way.

1253
01:21:48.210 --> 01:21:49.460
They're lucky to have you.

1254
01:21:49.540 --> 01:21:52.880
No. I'm the lucky one. I'm learning
from people a lot smarter than I am.

1255
01:21:53.960 --> 01:21:55.050
Matt.

1256
01:21:55.130 --> 01:21:56.590
they're not smarter than you.

1257
01:21:57.050 --> 01:21:58.840
I mean. they can't be.

1258
01:22:00.340 --> 01:22:01.460
They're my friends.

1259
01:22:02.250 --> 01:22:04.710
Hey. Look. I'm sorry. I didn't...

1260
01:22:04.790 --> 01:22:06.340
- No.
- Just... Matt.

1261
01:22:07.050 --> 01:22:08.130
Don't talk like that.

1262
01:22:09.710 --> 01:22:10.750
Hello?

1263
01:22:11.500 --> 01:22:12.500
It's Florance.

1264
01:22:14.000 --> 01:22:15.500
I've got four white customers here

1265
01:22:15.590 --> 01:22:18.000
saying they wanna withdraw all their money
from the bank

1266
01:22:18.090 --> 01:22:19.380
because they think it's owned

1267
01:22:19.460 --> 01:22:22.500
by the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People.

1268
01:22:35.540 --> 01:22:37.250
This was on the door at Mainland.

1269
01:22:39.130 --> 01:22:40.130
Subtle.

1270
01:22:41.170 --> 01:22:44.880
Five white customers withdrew
all their money in the past two days.

1271
01:22:45.250 --> 01:22:47.670
Nine were convinced by Florance to stay.

1272
01:22:48.290 --> 01:22:49.290
Fitting.

1273
01:22:49.380 --> 01:22:54.000
Considering Florance probably the one
who started and spread the rumors himself.

1274
01:22:54.090 --> 01:22:56.000
What? Why would you say that?

1275
01:22:57.420 --> 01:22:59.380
Told you long time ago. Bernard.

1276
01:22:59.460 --> 01:23:00.460
I don't trust people.

1277
01:23:01.380 --> 01:23:03.340
Especially white people. I remember.

1278
01:23:03.420 --> 01:23:07.420
No. what I said was white and black.

1279
01:23:07.500 --> 01:23:10.750
The difference is.
when a white person screws you over.

1280
01:23:10.840 --> 01:23:14.050
they can count on other white folks
out there to look the other way.

1281
01:23:14.130 --> 01:23:17.500
And just knowing that
brings out the worst in people.

1282
01:23:18.710 --> 01:23:22.090
How can you be so pessimistic
and still get out the bed in the morning?

1283
01:23:23.170 --> 01:23:25.630
Even a rigged game's fun to play. Bernard.

1284
01:23:35.420 --> 01:23:36.420
Matt Steiner?

1285
01:23:37.250 --> 01:23:38.420
Yes.

1286
01:23:38.500 --> 01:23:41.460
I'm an examiner with the office
of the Comptroller of the Currency.

1287
01:23:43.340 --> 01:23:44.420
How can I help you?

1288
01:23:53.130 --> 01:23:54.130
Hello?

1289
01:23:54.210 --> 01:23:56.540
A federal bank examiner
just left my office.

1290
01:23:56.630 --> 01:23:58.340
<i>I thought that wasn't until next month.</i>

1291
01:23:58.420 --> 01:24:00.170
No. I meant Marlin. not Mainland.

1292
01:24:02.460 --> 01:24:03.590
What did he say?

1293
01:24:04.460 --> 01:24:06.920
To get the master books out.
He's coming back in an hour.

1294
01:24:08.500 --> 01:24:09.500
Shit.

1295
01:24:11.590 --> 01:24:12.630
This can't be chance.

1296
01:24:12.710 --> 01:24:13.880
Matt's not ready.

1297
01:24:13.960 --> 01:24:14.960
Well. how could he be?

1298
01:24:15.050 --> 01:24:16.460
And he's gonna get tripped up.

1299
01:24:16.540 --> 01:24:17.840
We can't let that happen.

1300
01:24:17.920 --> 01:24:21.750
I'd have to be sitting in the room next to
him the whole time for it not to happen.

1301
01:24:21.840 --> 01:24:23.920
And I can't exactly do that. now can I?

1302
01:24:24.000 --> 01:24:25.920
Well. you could do something close to it.

1303
01:24:28.170 --> 01:24:29.750
There's gotta be another way.

1304
01:24:32.630 --> 01:24:35.340
Well. Joe's not too proud
to put on a chauffeur's uniform.

1305
01:24:35.420 --> 01:24:38.090
Well. Joe was born
with a silver spoon in his mouth.

1306
01:24:38.170 --> 01:24:39.710
For him it's like playing dress-up.

1307
01:24:39.790 --> 01:24:42.460
Well. I wasn't.
I was barely born with a spoon.

1308
01:24:42.540 --> 01:24:45.210
How many times have I worn this uniform
to help this business?

1309
01:24:45.290 --> 01:24:46.290
You're...

1310
01:24:46.840 --> 01:24:48.340
- A woman?
- Yeah.

1311
01:24:50.540 --> 01:24:51.420
I love you. Bernard.

1312
01:24:51.500 --> 01:24:53.440
But how is that any different
from a white man telling you

1313
01:24:53.460 --> 01:24:55.540
you shouldn't mind
some daily assault on your dignity

1314
01:24:55.630 --> 01:24:56.630
because you're black?

1315
01:25:56.710 --> 01:25:59.090
Should've took limo driver
when you had the chance.

1316
01:26:00.340 --> 01:26:03.090
I don't like what hats do
to the shape of my face.

1317
01:26:03.800 --> 01:26:05.420
You made an actual joke.

1318
01:26:05.500 --> 01:26:07.500
Well. what else can I do
in this situation?

1319
01:26:09.290 --> 01:26:11.750
See. you find out how life really works.

1320
01:26:12.840 --> 01:26:14.210
can't do nothing but laugh.

1321
01:26:18.130 --> 01:26:20.500
You sure you don't want
a coffee or anything?

1322
01:26:20.590 --> 01:26:21.590
No. thank you.

1323
01:26:21.670 --> 01:26:23.210
A cold water maybe?

1324
01:26:23.290 --> 01:26:25.170
As of close of business Friday.

1325
01:26:25.250 --> 01:26:28.840
the total number of loans delinquent
beyond 60 days was under 5%?

1326
01:26:30.250 --> 01:26:31.250
Yes.

1327
01:26:31.340 --> 01:26:32.750
What was the exact percentage?

1328
01:26:35.670 --> 01:26:36.960
3%.

1329
01:26:46.420 --> 01:26:50.000
We are discussing
confidential information.

1330
01:26:50.460 --> 01:26:52.380
I'm sure the janitor
wouldn't understand it.

1331
01:26:52.460 --> 01:26:53.630
Someone else might.

1332
01:26:58.000 --> 01:26:59.590
Take me through this transaction.

1333
01:27:00.290 --> 01:27:03.880
That's a package of loans we bought
to increase our loan-to-capital ratio.

1334
01:27:06.380 --> 01:27:07.380
He's in trouble.

1335
01:27:10.210 --> 01:27:12.040
I can read the description myself.

1336
01:27:12.130 --> 01:27:14.420
I'm curious about this related charge.

1337
01:27:14.500 --> 01:27:20.630
$189.186.04
to Valley National Mortgage Company.

1338
01:27:21.210 --> 01:27:22.880
There's no description for that.

1339
01:27:23.380 --> 01:27:24.670
It's a broker's fee.

1340
01:27:26.500 --> 01:27:32.920
$189.000 as a finder's fee
for a $971.000 package of loans

1341
01:27:33.500 --> 01:27:35.420
sitting in an aggregator's office
in Houston?

1342
01:27:36.090 --> 01:27:37.630
That's a pretty hefty finder's fee.

1343
01:27:38.250 --> 01:27:42.710
No. 19.5%. but that includes payment
for future consultation.

1344
01:27:43.250 --> 01:27:45.090
Well. that's a strange arrangement.

1345
01:27:45.170 --> 01:27:46.590
Mr. Garrett and Mr. Morris?

1346
01:27:46.670 --> 01:27:48.920
Is that something that should concern you?

1347
01:27:49.000 --> 01:27:51.090
Aren't you here
to make sure my bank is sound?

1348
01:27:52.340 --> 01:27:54.380
Okay. let's turn to the loans themselves.

1349
01:27:55.460 --> 01:27:59.290
You paid $971.213 for these loans.

1350
01:27:59.380 --> 01:28:01.590
You have them valued as such
on your books.

1351
01:28:01.670 --> 01:28:03.000
Yes. of course.

1352
01:28:03.090 --> 01:28:06.420
Show me the methodology you used
to justify that book value.

1353
01:28:08.090 --> 01:28:09.460
I have an expert to do that.

1354
01:28:09.540 --> 01:28:10.630
Bring him in. please.

1355
01:28:12.840 --> 01:28:13.880
He's not in today.

1356
01:28:18.920 --> 01:28:21.710
But I can check his files.

1357
01:28:22.210 --> 01:28:23.340
Please.

1358
01:28:37.290 --> 01:28:41.090
He wants to know the exact methodology
we used to value the loans in the package.

1359
01:28:41.170 --> 01:28:42.170
Okay.

1360
01:28:42.960 --> 01:28:43.960
Pay attention.

1361
01:28:45.000 --> 01:28:46.960
It's a standard present value equation.

1362
01:28:47.960 --> 01:28:51.040
This is an individual loan's
monthly payment schedule.

1363
01:28:51.130 --> 01:28:53.750
Now. adjust that
with the risk factor for default.

1364
01:28:53.840 --> 01:28:55.920
Standard 5% in Texas.

1365
01:28:56.380 --> 01:28:57.380
That's what I used.

1366
01:28:58.420 --> 01:28:59.540
Tear that out for me.

1367
01:28:59.630 --> 01:29:01.520
You can't go in the room
with that piece of paper.

1368
01:29:01.540 --> 01:29:03.170
It's got Bernard's handwriting on it.

1369
01:29:03.250 --> 01:29:04.270
- Memorize it.
- No. I can't.

1370
01:29:04.290 --> 01:29:06.500
Sure you can. You got a great memory.

1371
01:29:06.590 --> 01:29:07.460
No. I'm too nervous.

1372
01:29:07.540 --> 01:29:08.670
Hey. listen.

1373
01:29:08.750 --> 01:29:11.670
You fail this test
and he's gonna write down those loans

1374
01:29:11.750 --> 01:29:13.510
and it'll threaten
the stability of the bank.

1375
01:29:13.540 --> 01:29:14.540
Your bank.

1376
01:29:15.000 --> 01:29:16.090
This is your bank. Matt.

1377
01:29:16.170 --> 01:29:18.590
Now. pull it together
and go out there and save it.

1378
01:29:20.460 --> 01:29:22.090
Okay. let me see that one more time.

1379
01:29:27.630 --> 01:29:30.800
Okay. I have the methodology.

1380
01:29:30.880 --> 01:29:31.960
Put a pin in that.

1381
01:29:32.040 --> 01:29:34.670
I found problems with individual loans
while you were gone.

1382
01:29:35.340 --> 01:29:37.460
I valued those loans conservatively.

1383
01:29:37.880 --> 01:29:39.170
We didn't do anything wrong.

1384
01:29:39.250 --> 01:29:42.710
They wanna shut us down.
they got plenty ways they can do that.

1385
01:29:43.130 --> 01:29:45.130
"5% default rate?

1386
01:29:46.000 --> 01:29:48.500
Hell. What if there's a drought?

1387
01:29:48.590 --> 01:29:50.920
You niggers need to value them loans

1388
01:29:51.000 --> 01:29:54.920
assuming there's gonna be
a once-in-a-generation drought.

1389
01:29:55.420 --> 01:29:58.000
25% default rate for y'all."

1390
01:30:00.040 --> 01:30:02.540
This loan's gonna have to be
sold off immediately.

1391
01:30:03.710 --> 01:30:05.050
And this one.

1392
01:30:05.460 --> 01:30:07.420
And this one.

1393
01:30:07.500 --> 01:30:09.550
Why? Why? What's wrong with them?

1394
01:30:09.630 --> 01:30:11.500
Well. that loan is for $21.000.

1395
01:30:11.590 --> 01:30:14.170
Your capital account is $200.000.

1396
01:30:14.250 --> 01:30:15.250
Okay.

1397
01:30:17.460 --> 01:30:19.710
You don't understand why that's a problem.
do you?

1398
01:30:21.250 --> 01:30:25.750
The National Banking Act specifies that no
bank shall have a single loan on the books

1399
01:30:25.840 --> 01:30:28.170
that exceeds 10% of equity capital.

1400
01:30:28.250 --> 01:30:30.380
Or $20.000 in this case.

1401
01:30:31.290 --> 01:30:32.290
Right.

1402
01:30:35.880 --> 01:30:37.590
Okay. but this one's only 4.000.

1403
01:30:37.670 --> 01:30:39.880
It's for a 25-year term.
Same with this one.

1404
01:30:41.380 --> 01:30:43.880
A bank of this size
is limited to 20-year terms.

1405
01:30:45.040 --> 01:30:49.170
And this loan is legal on its face.
but it's three months delinquent.

1406
01:30:50.090 --> 01:30:53.000
I'm not gonna require you to sell it.
but I'm gonna classify it.

1407
01:30:53.090 --> 01:30:55.420
Take its value down on your books by 40%

1408
01:30:55.500 --> 01:30:57.420
to account for the elevated risk
of default.

1409
01:31:03.670 --> 01:31:06.420
Hold on. I'll be right back.

1410
01:31:11.840 --> 01:31:13.880
How the hell
did these loans get in the package?

1411
01:31:13.960 --> 01:31:15.840
- I don't know.
- Unacceptable.

1412
01:31:15.920 --> 01:31:17.920
I looked over every individual loan. Matt.

1413
01:31:18.000 --> 01:31:20.840
There was nothing over $20.000.
Nothing over 20 years.

1414
01:31:20.920 --> 01:31:23.170
Did you look at the loans
when you picked them up?

1415
01:31:23.840 --> 01:31:25.920
Did you look at the goddamn loans?

1416
01:31:26.000 --> 01:31:28.160
Yes. I looked through them.
Maybe not carefully enough.

1417
01:31:28.210 --> 01:31:29.210
I read the top sheet...

1418
01:31:29.290 --> 01:31:30.420
Unbelievable.

1419
01:31:30.960 --> 01:31:32.630
Well. they can't lie on the top sheet.

1420
01:31:32.710 --> 01:31:35.290
Matt. there aren't any limiters.

1421
01:31:35.380 --> 01:31:36.170
What?

1422
01:31:36.250 --> 01:31:39.170
There isn't anything on this top sheet
about individual loan limits.

1423
01:31:39.250 --> 01:31:40.840
dollar amounts or durations.

1424
01:31:40.920 --> 01:31:42.170
They're all averages.

1425
01:31:43.380 --> 01:31:44.500
They didn't lie.

1426
01:31:44.590 --> 01:31:46.500
They just hid the shit in the averages.

1427
01:31:46.590 --> 01:31:48.920
How the hell did our lawyer miss that?

1428
01:31:49.550 --> 01:31:51.630
- I couldn't use O'Keefe.
- What?

1429
01:31:51.710 --> 01:31:54.390
Bernard checked the properties so fast
I moved up the purchase date.

1430
01:31:54.460 --> 01:31:56.270
O'Keefe couldn't make it.
so I hired someone else.

1431
01:31:56.290 --> 01:31:57.890
- How did you find him?
- I asked around.

1432
01:31:57.920 --> 01:32:00.290
You asked... He asked around.
What the hell's that mean?

1433
01:32:00.380 --> 01:32:03.130
We told you you weren't ready
to run your own bank. We told you.

1434
01:32:03.210 --> 01:32:05.040
You forced our hand. Now here we are.

1435
01:32:05.130 --> 01:32:06.130
Whoa. whoa. whoa.

1436
01:32:06.840 --> 01:32:11.500
Who exactly did you ask
to find this lawyer?

1437
01:32:13.880 --> 01:32:14.880
Who. Matt?

1438
01:32:15.710 --> 01:32:16.710
Florance.

1439
01:32:17.790 --> 01:32:18.920
Florance?

1440
01:32:19.500 --> 01:32:21.090
You asked Florance?

1441
01:32:22.460 --> 01:32:24.750
He switched the goddamn mortgages.

1442
01:32:24.840 --> 01:32:26.000
Why? Why would he do that?

1443
01:32:26.090 --> 01:32:27.420
To kill Marlin.

1444
01:32:27.500 --> 01:32:31.210
And the worst part is I have to learn
about it here. in this ridiculous outfit.

1445
01:32:31.290 --> 01:32:32.460
that you helped him do it!

1446
01:32:32.550 --> 01:32:34.090
No. that's gotta be illegal. right?

1447
01:32:35.090 --> 01:32:36.670
What does he get from that. anyway?

1448
01:32:36.750 --> 01:32:38.170
Leverage.

1449
01:32:38.250 --> 01:32:40.460
Against us at Mainland.

1450
01:32:41.250 --> 01:32:43.040
Or maybe just to watch us fail.

1451
01:32:52.290 --> 01:32:58.040
We have to sell 27 bad loans in a week
and cover all the markdowns ourselves.

1452
01:32:59.340 --> 01:33:01.210
We're gonna lose $300.000.

1453
01:33:01.290 --> 01:33:06.460
unless Matt Steiner can make Marlin
the most successful bank in Texas history.

1454
01:33:10.000 --> 01:33:11.790
Or you could let it close.

1455
01:33:14.040 --> 01:33:15.500
Matt got you here. you didn't.

1456
01:33:15.590 --> 01:33:17.710
No. I did.

1457
01:33:18.550 --> 01:33:22.210
Soon as I thought I was clever enough
to come down here and take on all of this.

1458
01:33:23.000 --> 01:33:24.040
Joe warned me.

1459
01:33:25.170 --> 01:33:26.170
You warned me.

1460
01:33:28.630 --> 01:33:30.630
My daddy warned me when I was 13.

1461
01:33:35.130 --> 01:33:38.590
If this was easy. somebody else
would have done it a long time ago.

1462
01:33:44.380 --> 01:33:46.210
So. you're just gonna walk away from it?

1463
01:33:46.750 --> 01:33:48.290
It's the only rational thing to do.

1464
01:33:48.380 --> 01:33:49.840
No. we could sue the bastards.

1465
01:33:49.920 --> 01:33:53.250
You signed a document saying
you knew exactly what you were buying.

1466
01:33:53.340 --> 01:33:55.170
But the lawyer lied to me. We can sue him.

1467
01:33:55.250 --> 01:33:57.420
Maybe you can. Matt. but we can't.

1468
01:33:58.040 --> 01:34:00.750
Me and Bernard can't win that case.
not in Texas.

1469
01:34:01.300 --> 01:34:04.340
Plus. Marlin will be gone by then anyway.

1470
01:34:04.420 --> 01:34:07.130
I'm not gonna lose Marlin.
There's gotta be something I can do.

1471
01:34:07.210 --> 01:34:08.210
Look. I'm sorry. Matt.

1472
01:34:08.300 --> 01:34:11.170
I know it was your baby.
but I need you to focus on Mainland now.

1473
01:34:13.550 --> 01:34:14.550
Well. how?

1474
01:34:14.630 --> 01:34:16.040
Keep an eye on Florance.

1475
01:34:16.130 --> 01:34:18.250
And make sure when white folks
come in that bank.

1476
01:34:18.340 --> 01:34:20.670
they see a white man
in the president's office

1477
01:34:20.750 --> 01:34:22.540
so they won't pull their deposits.

1478
01:34:43.380 --> 01:34:44.590
Garrett residence.

1479
01:34:45.130 --> 01:34:47.250
Yes. he's here. Just a moment.

1480
01:34:47.750 --> 01:34:49.210
Joe. it's for you.

1481
01:34:51.380 --> 01:34:52.550
Yeah. this is Joe.

1482
01:34:52.630 --> 01:34:53.690
You didn't hear this from me.

1483
01:34:53.710 --> 01:34:57.090
but I got a friend at the Comptroller's
office who kind of looks out for me.

1484
01:34:57.790 --> 01:34:58.960
Called me yesterday to say

1485
01:34:59.040 --> 01:35:02.130
Matt Steiner managed to get all
"must sell" loans off Marlin's books.

1486
01:35:02.630 --> 01:35:03.460
That don't matter.

1487
01:35:03.540 --> 01:35:06.100
'cause we decided we ain't gonna
put no more money in there anyhow.

1488
01:35:06.130 --> 01:35:07.840
At face value. No discount.

1489
01:35:07.920 --> 01:35:10.540
Which means Marlin's in the black again.
fully solvent...

1490
01:35:11.750 --> 01:35:13.040
without capital from you.

1491
01:35:14.040 --> 01:35:17.300
Who the hell would pay face value
for those piece of shit loans?

1492
01:35:17.920 --> 01:35:19.840
Mainland bank in Willis. Texas.

1493
01:35:19.920 --> 01:35:21.040
Say what?

1494
01:35:21.590 --> 01:35:23.420
Son of a bitch!

1495
01:35:46.920 --> 01:35:48.210
What the hell are you doing?

1496
01:35:48.300 --> 01:35:49.880
You had Mainland pay face value

1497
01:35:49.960 --> 01:35:52.540
for the loans the feds
already had you mark down at Marlin?

1498
01:35:52.630 --> 01:35:53.790
It's just temporary.

1499
01:35:53.880 --> 01:35:56.130
- It's fraud.
- No. if we classify them differently...

1500
01:35:56.210 --> 01:35:59.040
If you keep this up.
you're gonna sink both banks. Matt.

1501
01:35:59.790 --> 01:36:00.920
Get the books.

1502
01:36:01.590 --> 01:36:03.920
- Shouldn't we wait until...
- Get the goddamn books now.

1503
01:36:22.880 --> 01:36:25.040
All I did was transfer the...

1504
01:36:25.130 --> 01:36:27.500
Matthew Steiner.
president of Mainland Bank?

1505
01:36:28.710 --> 01:36:29.710
- Yes.
- I'm Norman Dunn.

1506
01:36:29.790 --> 01:36:32.710
Deputy Comptroller of the Currency
for the Southern District.

1507
01:36:32.790 --> 01:36:36.040
The Treasury Department has revoked
Mainland's license to do banking.

1508
01:36:36.130 --> 01:36:39.840
Your bank is being placed in FDIC
receivership per the National Banking Act.

1509
01:36:39.920 --> 01:36:41.840
This is Mr. Amos of the FDIC.

1510
01:36:42.250 --> 01:36:44.550
Mr. Steiner. you're fired.

1511
01:36:44.630 --> 01:36:46.480
I'm going to need to escort you
from the building now.

1512
01:36:46.500 --> 01:36:48.460
Please leave the ledgers where they are.

1513
01:36:50.880 --> 01:36:52.090
Ladies and gentlemen.

1514
01:36:52.170 --> 01:36:56.210
the United States Treasury Department
has closed this bank until further notice.

1515
01:36:56.300 --> 01:37:00.380
All deposits up to $10.000
are insured by the federal government.

1516
01:37:00.460 --> 01:37:04.290
Upon FDIC review of the bank's books.
your money will be returned to you.

1517
01:37:04.790 --> 01:37:06.710
The building is now closed to the public.

1518
01:37:06.790 --> 01:37:08.880
We must ask that you leave.

1519
01:37:18.540 --> 01:37:21.090
I'm so sorry.
I thought that I could save both...

1520
01:37:21.170 --> 01:37:22.210
Get out of my face.

1521
01:37:22.960 --> 01:37:25.090
- Bernard Garrett and Joseph Morris?
- Yes.

1522
01:37:25.170 --> 01:37:27.000
- FBI. You're under arrest.
- For what?

1523
01:37:27.090 --> 01:37:28.230
Turn around and face the wall.

1524
01:37:28.250 --> 01:37:30.650
No. What are we under arrest for?
What did we do that's illegal?

1525
01:37:30.670 --> 01:37:31.900
- The judge will tell you that.
- No. screw the judge.

1526
01:37:31.920 --> 01:37:33.770
- You tell me what we did that's illegal.
- Bernard.

1527
01:37:33.790 --> 01:37:35.100
- What's he complaining about?
- I get it.

1528
01:37:35.130 --> 01:37:37.980
A black man makes some money and it's okay
as long as he keeps to himself.

1529
01:37:38.000 --> 01:37:40.310
But if he try to bring other brothers up.
that's intolerable.

1530
01:37:40.340 --> 01:37:42.000
This is happening. Mr. Garrett.

1531
01:37:42.090 --> 01:37:45.250
The only question to ask yourself
is do you want to get hurt fighting it?

1532
01:37:46.130 --> 01:37:48.130
- Hey. get off of him!
- Bernard. no! No!

1533
01:37:53.130 --> 01:37:54.130
Come on.

1534
01:38:04.750 --> 01:38:07.920
<i>The state banking charges
have all been dropped.</i>

1535
01:38:08.000 --> 01:38:11.670
The federal charges.
however. are all still in place.

1536
01:38:12.500 --> 01:38:16.250
Now. it's my feeling
that we're in a political space here.

1537
01:38:16.630 --> 01:38:18.290
So if we play our cards right.

1538
01:38:18.790 --> 01:38:21.170
we'll be able to get
those charges dropped as well.

1539
01:38:21.250 --> 01:38:22.340
Political how?

1540
01:38:23.170 --> 01:38:25.340
Well. Senator John McClellan of Arkansas

1541
01:38:25.420 --> 01:38:29.460
is holding a set of hearings
on federally funded banks.

1542
01:38:29.540 --> 01:38:35.040
The goal seems to be to shit all over
the so-called "lax oversight"

1543
01:38:35.130 --> 01:38:36.960
that our Treasury provides.

1544
01:38:37.540 --> 01:38:41.500
so as to justify his committee
expanding its jurisdiction.

1545
01:38:41.590 --> 01:38:45.920
Thereby ensuring a steady stream
of campaign donations

1546
01:38:46.000 --> 01:38:48.540
and favors from the banking industry.

1547
01:38:48.630 --> 01:38:50.630
So. what does that have to do with me?

1548
01:38:50.710 --> 01:38:52.790
You want the stated
or the unstated version?

1549
01:38:54.170 --> 01:38:55.170
Unstated.

1550
01:38:55.250 --> 01:38:57.050
"We need to change these laws.

1551
01:38:57.130 --> 01:38:58.420
And I mean quick!

1552
01:38:58.500 --> 01:39:03.090
Or niggers like these can own banks
and loan money to other niggers."

1553
01:39:03.170 --> 01:39:04.170
That.

1554
01:39:05.170 --> 01:39:06.840
On the bright side. Bernard.

1555
01:39:06.920 --> 01:39:10.670
'cause we fit so neatly
into McClellan's power grab.

1556
01:39:11.170 --> 01:39:15.630
the whole country's talkin' about
how two Negroes managed to buy two banks

1557
01:39:15.710 --> 01:39:19.840
full of white folks' money in Texas
and loan it to other Negroes.

1558
01:39:20.210 --> 01:39:23.550
I thought McClellan was one of the first
people to stand up to McCarthyism.

1559
01:39:23.630 --> 01:39:24.460
He was.

1560
01:39:24.540 --> 01:39:26.630
So he must be a decent man. right?

1561
01:39:29.880 --> 01:39:33.960
You know. Bernard. I don't have
the ability to look into a man's soul.

1562
01:39:35.170 --> 01:39:36.790
But I will tell you this...

1563
01:39:37.380 --> 01:39:39.750
he means to make a point
with these hearings.

1564
01:39:39.840 --> 01:39:41.920
And if you want
to help him make that point.

1565
01:39:42.500 --> 01:39:47.460
I highly doubt that you're gonna have any
problem with any kind of criminal charges.

1566
01:39:49.590 --> 01:39:51.290
So. where's Matt in all this?

1567
01:39:51.380 --> 01:39:54.090
Now. that is a good question.

1568
01:40:03.210 --> 01:40:04.750
My lawyer doesn't want me here.

1569
01:40:05.750 --> 01:40:08.540
Then your lawyer doesn't have
your best interests at heart. Matt.

1570
01:40:09.050 --> 01:40:11.750
Because we can make a deal here
that could save your life.

1571
01:40:11.840 --> 01:40:13.050
How does that work exactly?

1572
01:40:14.290 --> 01:40:15.290
You're gonna...

1573
01:40:15.880 --> 01:40:18.300
give me back my money? My house?

1574
01:40:19.380 --> 01:40:20.590
Hardly.

1575
01:40:20.670 --> 01:40:22.750
But I can give you immunity.

1576
01:40:23.210 --> 01:40:25.340
And you might avoid
being called to account

1577
01:40:25.960 --> 01:40:28.710
for lying to the public
on 23 separate occasions

1578
01:40:28.790 --> 01:40:31.880
about the true ownership
of the Mainland and Marlin banks.

1579
01:40:32.880 --> 01:40:35.790
Fraudulently valuing loans in these banks.

1580
01:40:36.840 --> 01:40:40.960
Illegally transferring said loans
between the banks in question.

1581
01:40:44.540 --> 01:40:45.790
It's an easy story to tell.

1582
01:40:46.590 --> 01:40:49.790
how these two men manipulated you.

1583
01:40:50.880 --> 01:40:55.090
used you to make money by duping everyday
citizens into thinking you were the boss.

1584
01:40:55.170 --> 01:40:58.630
when really it was
two Negroes pulling the strings.

1585
01:41:00.590 --> 01:41:03.000
But they didn't force me
to do the things I did.

1586
01:41:03.960 --> 01:41:05.630
They were careful to follow the law.

1587
01:41:05.710 --> 01:41:08.170
You won't find any evidence
that they committed a crime.

1588
01:41:08.540 --> 01:41:10.460
See. that's the thing about banking crime.

1589
01:41:11.460 --> 01:41:13.380
there's always a subjective element to it.

1590
01:41:14.460 --> 01:41:15.500
Now.

1591
01:41:16.130 --> 01:41:18.790
these two Negroes earned...

1592
01:41:20.540 --> 01:41:23.340
189.000 between the two of them.

1593
01:41:24.340 --> 01:41:30.170
off a $971.000 purchase of mortgages
that in fact were worth 663.000.

1594
01:41:30.250 --> 01:41:34.130
See. that is a misuse of bank funds
in my book.

1595
01:41:35.130 --> 01:41:36.790
And a misuse of bank funds is a crime.

1596
01:41:36.880 --> 01:41:38.380
It's more complicated than that.

1597
01:41:38.460 --> 01:41:40.040
I don't think it is. Mr. Steiner.

1598
01:41:41.540 --> 01:41:45.340
Unless you're telling me they didn't force
you to buy these dog-shit mortgages...

1599
01:41:47.340 --> 01:41:50.710
so they could bilk the bank
of $189.000 of commission.

1600
01:41:53.420 --> 01:41:54.840
Then maybe they are innocent

1601
01:41:56.590 --> 01:41:58.670
and maybe
someone else needs to go to prison.

1602
01:42:06.670 --> 01:42:08.670
I'm really sorry I ever brought him in.

1603
01:42:08.750 --> 01:42:10.170
You didn't force me to hire him.

1604
01:42:10.670 --> 01:42:12.800
Joe warned me a dozen times as well.

1605
01:42:15.340 --> 01:42:17.130
Just wanted to believe in him. I guess.

1606
01:42:19.710 --> 01:42:23.090
I hope whoever owns this place is taking
good care of you for the renovation.

1607
01:42:26.090 --> 01:42:27.090
He is...

1608
01:42:28.800 --> 01:42:29.800
'cause it's me.

1609
01:42:33.210 --> 01:42:34.210
Yeah.

1610
01:42:35.090 --> 01:42:36.630
Yeah.

1611
01:42:56.250 --> 01:42:59.340
<i>So. it's your testimony that
you've always been under the direction</i>

1612
01:42:59.420 --> 01:43:01.130
of Bernard Garrett and Joe Morris.

1613
01:43:01.210 --> 01:43:02.340
Is that correct?

1614
01:43:06.000 --> 01:43:07.250
It is. Yes.

1615
01:43:08.170 --> 01:43:10.380
You ever refuse an order
from Garrett or Morris?

1616
01:43:12.130 --> 01:43:16.290
For example. the initial purchase
of mortgages by the Marlin bank.

1617
01:43:17.090 --> 01:43:21.670
for which Garrett and Morris
were compensated $189.000.

1618
01:43:22.540 --> 01:43:26.420
or Mainland Bank's subsequent purchase
at grossly inflated prices

1619
01:43:27.340 --> 01:43:29.170
of problem mortgages from Marlin?

1620
01:43:32.290 --> 01:43:35.170
They were my employers.
I carried out their wishes to the letter.

1621
01:44:19.090 --> 01:44:21.290
<i>I'm surprised
you requested this meeting. Melvin.</i>

1622
01:44:22.130 --> 01:44:25.250
It seemed my offer required
a simple answer. yes or no.

1623
01:44:26.040 --> 01:44:28.380
Especially given
how solid Steiner was today.

1624
01:44:29.210 --> 01:44:31.340
Well. John. Bernard's not the kind of man

1625
01:44:31.420 --> 01:44:34.170
to make a deal
without checking all the details.

1626
01:44:36.090 --> 01:44:38.710
It seems to me
that a large part of his purported defense

1627
01:44:38.800 --> 01:44:39.920
is that he did just that.

1628
01:44:41.920 --> 01:44:44.880
You want me to put the banking rules
on trial in my testimony.

1629
01:44:45.290 --> 01:44:46.710
I want you to tell the truth.

1630
01:44:47.540 --> 01:44:49.170
Which should have that result. yes.

1631
01:44:50.920 --> 01:44:54.380
The rules allowed you
to hide your identity from the public

1632
01:44:54.460 --> 01:44:59.840
and take the successive actions that led
to two national banks becoming insolvent.

1633
01:45:01.420 --> 01:45:05.210
risking the savings
of thousands of innocent depositors.

1634
01:45:06.460 --> 01:45:08.340
You and I see the truth very differently.

1635
01:45:10.170 --> 01:45:11.460
Son. I'm from Arkansas.

1636
01:45:12.090 --> 01:45:15.540
You don't have to tell me that Negroes
sometimes get the short end of the stick.

1637
01:45:16.000 --> 01:45:17.130
"Sometimes."

1638
01:45:20.130 --> 01:45:21.590
We're not gonna change that here.

1639
01:45:23.800 --> 01:45:27.050
The truth is. whatever obstacles
they put in your way.

1640
01:45:27.130 --> 01:45:29.630
you kept your head down.
did your business.

1641
01:45:30.000 --> 01:45:33.670
became one of the richest Negroes
in the country.

1642
01:45:37.750 --> 01:45:39.590
You were living the American dream

1643
01:45:41.800 --> 01:45:46.840
before you decided to go mucking around
with the social order in Texas.

1644
01:45:48.960 --> 01:45:50.340
Might be a lesson there.

1645
01:45:51.040 --> 01:45:52.130
You have a choice now.

1646
01:45:54.210 --> 01:45:56.090
Take the immunity deal.

1647
01:45:56.170 --> 01:45:59.840
Go in there and confirm
what Steiner just told us.

1648
01:45:59.920 --> 01:46:05.250
that you took advantage of lax rules
in order to enrich yourself.

1649
01:46:06.210 --> 01:46:09.460
And let Congress fix those rules.
and you'll be a free man.

1650
01:46:10.550 --> 01:46:13.130
Or you can refuse the deal...

1651
01:46:14.210 --> 01:46:15.380
and say whatever you want.

1652
01:46:17.550 --> 01:46:18.550
But just know.

1653
01:46:20.090 --> 01:46:25.750
after you're done saying your piece
about racism and the plight of the Negro.

1654
01:46:25.840 --> 01:46:28.550
we're gonna compare your testimony
point for point

1655
01:46:28.630 --> 01:46:30.670
with what we heard
from Steiner and Florance.

1656
01:46:30.750 --> 01:46:32.500
and a whole bunch of other white people.

1657
01:46:32.590 --> 01:46:36.340
Well. thank God the Constitution
doesn't make those types of distinctions.

1658
01:46:37.460 --> 01:46:39.250
Well. at the end of all that.

1659
01:46:39.340 --> 01:46:41.460
a determination will be made
by a court of law

1660
01:46:41.550 --> 01:46:43.210
to decide who's telling the truth...

1661
01:46:44.250 --> 01:46:45.250
and who's lying.

1662
01:46:46.840 --> 01:46:48.340
And the liars are going to prison.

1663
01:46:53.090 --> 01:46:55.090
Sure is pretty from the outside.

1664
01:46:59.090 --> 01:47:00.210
Guess you were right.

1665
01:47:01.000 --> 01:47:04.130
It was too early
for two Negroes to own a bank in Texas.

1666
01:47:05.710 --> 01:47:06.710
Maybe.

1667
01:47:07.290 --> 01:47:09.290
Or maybe you were right to do it now.

1668
01:47:11.550 --> 01:47:12.630
Why?

1669
01:47:15.090 --> 01:47:16.290
Look where you ended up.

1670
01:47:18.920 --> 01:47:21.630
White people get to buy homes
and build businesses

1671
01:47:21.710 --> 01:47:23.380
because banks will loan them money.

1672
01:47:24.670 --> 01:47:25.960
Black people don't.

1673
01:47:26.040 --> 01:47:29.040
And maybe it is time that someone
shine a bright light on that now.

1674
01:47:29.630 --> 01:47:31.290
in order for things to change.

1675
01:47:32.550 --> 01:47:36.290
Well. if I shine the light too bright.
McClellan will get rid of my immunity.

1676
01:47:39.380 --> 01:47:41.090
What do you think I should do in there?

1677
01:47:43.130 --> 01:47:45.290
Everyone thought I was crazy to marry you.

1678
01:47:47.500 --> 01:47:50.040
You always thought differently
from everyone else.

1679
01:47:51.670 --> 01:47:54.000
But that's why
I fell in love with you. Bernard.

1680
01:47:55.170 --> 01:47:58.960
And whatever you decide to do
in there today is not gonna change that.

1681
01:48:12.380 --> 01:48:14.090
Would you mind giving me a minute?

1682
01:48:17.790 --> 01:48:20.040
Should I be jealous
you get to testify first?

1683
01:48:20.130 --> 01:48:21.210
No. man.

1684
01:48:22.040 --> 01:48:25.130
I'm just a warm-up act
for the criminal mastermind to follow.

1685
01:48:26.380 --> 01:48:28.130
Well. they gonna be disappointed as hell

1686
01:48:28.210 --> 01:48:30.210
because I plan to
blame all this shit on you.

1687
01:48:30.290 --> 01:48:32.380
Damn. That was my plan too.

1688
01:48:34.750 --> 01:48:36.630
You know. when I first laid eyes on you.

1689
01:48:36.710 --> 01:48:40.170
I thought you were this uptight.
square-ass Negro

1690
01:48:40.250 --> 01:48:42.550
who wouldn't know
whitey's hand was 'round his neck

1691
01:48:42.630 --> 01:48:44.250
if he was staring at it in a mirror.

1692
01:48:45.550 --> 01:48:47.500
Glad I made such a good first impression.

1693
01:48:49.040 --> 01:48:50.040
Turns out.

1694
01:48:50.960 --> 01:48:52.790
you a goddamn revolutionary.

1695
01:48:54.250 --> 01:48:55.840
You know. when I first met you.

1696
01:48:56.630 --> 01:48:59.210
I thought you were
an entitled playboy clown.

1697
01:49:01.250 --> 01:49:02.290
Man.

1698
01:49:03.750 --> 01:49:07.340
you saw things years before I did.

1699
01:49:08.840 --> 01:49:09.920
Even about myself.

1700
01:49:12.880 --> 01:49:14.290
five minutes after meeting me.

1701
01:49:43.210 --> 01:49:45.670
Committee calls Bernard S. Garrett
to testify.

1702
01:49:49.920 --> 01:49:52.250
Do you have his glasses?
He doesn't have his glasses.

1703
01:49:52.340 --> 01:49:53.500
He doesn't need 'em.

1704
01:49:54.000 --> 01:49:55.710
He's got to read his opening statement.

1705
01:49:56.210 --> 01:49:59.000
He doesn't need his glasses. He never has.

1706
01:50:01.590 --> 01:50:04.630
Mr. Garrett.
I think you understand the stakes.

1707
01:50:09.040 --> 01:50:10.380
We'll take your statement now.

1708
01:50:11.960 --> 01:50:13.040
Mr. Chairman.

1709
01:50:13.920 --> 01:50:18.790
Our nation's founding documents declare
that "all men are created equal"

1710
01:50:19.420 --> 01:50:21.170
and endeavor to create a society

1711
01:50:21.250 --> 01:50:24.380
where citizens receive
the equal protection of our laws.

1712
01:50:25.040 --> 01:50:26.170
It's a noble goal.

1713
01:50:27.170 --> 01:50:30.710
But we all know.
for many citizens it's a lie.

1714
01:50:32.920 --> 01:50:34.340
This hearing is supposed to be

1715
01:50:34.420 --> 01:50:39.960
about uncovering and reforming
unsafe banking practices.

1716
01:50:40.790 --> 01:50:42.000
But I think it's really about

1717
01:50:42.090 --> 01:50:47.000
how on earth did two black men
pull off owning a bank in Texas.

1718
01:50:47.090 --> 01:50:50.550
Mr. Garrett. I think you
should tread carefully now.

1719
01:50:52.170 --> 01:50:54.130
Well. I can talk at length about that.

1720
01:50:54.750 --> 01:50:57.920
Or I can sum it up with this.

1721
01:51:00.880 --> 01:51:01.880
The dress code.

1722
01:51:02.420 --> 01:51:04.210
Mr. Garrett. you are out of order. sir.

1723
01:51:04.300 --> 01:51:05.710
- I'm not finished.
- Out of order.

1724
01:51:05.790 --> 01:51:08.630
If you can't get a loan.
you can't own a home.

1725
01:51:08.710 --> 01:51:09.790
You can't start a business.

1726
01:51:09.840 --> 01:51:11.340
Mr. Garrett. you have been warned.

1727
01:51:11.420 --> 01:51:14.040
- Which means you can't build wealth.
- Mr. Garrett!

1728
01:51:14.130 --> 01:51:16.040
And you're excluded
from the American dream.

1729
01:51:16.130 --> 01:51:17.750
Sergeant-at-arms. remove the witness.

1730
01:51:17.840 --> 01:51:22.090
Why is it so important to you
to exclude an entire race of people

1731
01:51:22.170 --> 01:51:23.710
from the American dream?

1732
01:52:42.750 --> 01:52:44.630
Figures they'd let you out before me.

1733
01:52:44.710 --> 01:52:46.920
Man. they couldn't wait
to get rid of my ass.

1734
01:52:52.380 --> 01:52:53.590
Let's go home.

1735
01:52:55.460 --> 01:52:56.750
They took 'em all. remember?

1736
01:52:56.840 --> 01:52:58.090
Well. let's go somewhere.

1737
01:53:01.590 --> 01:53:03.000
What are you two laughing about?

1738
01:53:03.090 --> 01:53:04.340
They didn't take all of 'em.

1739
01:53:04.420 --> 01:53:07.170
They didn't know about the two
we bought next door to each other

1740
01:53:07.250 --> 01:53:08.250
in the Bahamas.

1741
01:53:08.340 --> 01:53:09.340
What?

1742
01:53:10.460 --> 01:53:11.920
Bernard. how did you do that?

1743
01:53:14.540 --> 01:53:16.920
<i>Matt called me
the night before he testified.</i>

1744
01:53:18.250 --> 01:53:19.550
<i>He was pretty broken up.</i>

1745
01:53:28.670 --> 01:53:29.670
<i>Hello?</i>

1746
01:53:30.300 --> 01:53:31.300
It's Matt.

1747
01:53:33.540 --> 01:53:34.540
Can we talk?

1748
01:53:35.790 --> 01:53:38.340
<i>He told me
he was facing 50 years in prison</i>

1749
01:53:38.420 --> 01:53:40.630
<i>if he didn't say
what they wanted him to say.</i>

1750
01:53:42.210 --> 01:53:44.210
<i>I told him to do what he had to do.</i>

1751
01:53:45.750 --> 01:53:48.460
<i>but since the government
hadn't taken all of our money yet.</i>

1752
01:53:52.540 --> 01:53:54.040
I asked him to do me a favor.

1752
01:53:55.305 --> 01:54:55.414
